        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "@justinmk said\r\n> ```\r\n> :echo fnamemodify('/foo/bar/baz', ':p')\r\n> ```\r\n> \r\n> returns:\r\n> \r\n> ```\r\n> /foo/bar/baz\r\n> ```\r\n\r\nIn NVIM v0.9.0, it returns `C:\\Users\\ACER\\\\foo\\bar\\baz`, where `C:\\Users\\ACER\\` is the current directory.  So it just appends the argument.\r\n\r\n> but gvim on Windows returns:\r\n> \r\n> ```\r\n> C:\\foo\\bar\\baz\r\n> ```\r\n\r\nTo remove possible misunderstanding, Vim decides/prepends the drive letter based on the current directory.  So it's not always `C:\\foo\\bar\\baz`.  If you're in, say, `E:\\dir1\\dir2`, then Vim will output `E:\\foo\\bar\\baz`.\r\n\r\n\r\n@blueyed said:\r\n> Also Neovim does not handle `:.` to remove the drive on Windows:\r\n> \r\n> This is working with Vim, but not Neovim:\r\n> \r\n> ```\r\n>     AssertEqual fnamemodify('C:/foo', ':.'), 'foo'\r\n>     AssertEqual fnamemodify('C:\\foo', ':.'), 'foo'\r\n> ```\r\n> \r\n> Neovim does not change the argument, i.e. returns 'C:/foo' and 'C:\\foo'.\r\n\r\nI get the same result on Vim v9.0.1472.  I don't have `AssertEqual`, but `:echo fnamemodify('C:/foo', ':.')` on Vim returns `C:/foo`, like Neovim.",
            "created_at": "2023-05-13T07:03:03Z",
